Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is BERT?
AI Response

BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) is a pre-trained transformer model that
understands context from both directions in a sentence, excelling at NLP classification tasks.

Example 1.2

User

What is machine learning?
AI Response

Machine learning is a branch of artificial intelligence that enables systems to learn and improve from
experience without being explicitly programmed.

Example 1.3

User

What is a GAN?
AI Response

A Generative Adversarial Network pits a generator (creates fake data) against a discriminator (identifies
fakes), training each other until the generator produces realistic data.

Example 1.4

User

What is an epoch?
AI Response

An epoch is one full pass through the entire training dataset. Multiple epochs are used, and the number is a
key hyperparameter affecting model convergence.

Example 1.5

User

What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response

Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.

Example 1.6

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.7

User

What is dropout?
AI Response



Dropout randomly sets a fraction of neuron activations to zero during training, preventing co-adaptation of
neurons and reducing overfitting.

Example 1.8

User

What is word embedding?
AI Response

Word embeddings map words to dense vectors where similar words are nearby. Word2Vec, GloVe, and
FastText are popular methods, used as NLP model input features.

Example 1.9

User

What is gradient descent?
AI Response

Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm that iteratively adjusts model parameters in the direction
opposite to the gradient of the loss function to find a minimum.

Example 1.10

User

What is mean squared error?
AI Response

MSE is (1/n) * sum of (predicted - actual)^2. It penalizes large errors heavily and is a standard loss function
for regression tasks, sensitive to outliers.



